1. Prepare Your DatasetThe code expects a dataset in a .zip format stored in your Google Drive.
Upload to Drive: Ensure your dataset (e.g., archive.zip) is uploaded to a folder named datasets in your My Drive.
Structure: The zip file should contain two main folders: Training and Testing. 
Inside each, there should be subfolders for each class: glioma, meningioma, notumor, and pituitary.

2. Setup Google Colab
Go to Google Colab.
Create a New Notebook.
Enable GPU: Go to Edit > Notebook settings > Hardware accelerator and select T4 GPU. This is essential for training the VGG16 model efficiently.

3. Execute the Code Blocks
Copy and paste the code into separate cells and run them in order:
Step A: Mount Drive & Extract: Run the first block to link your Google Drive and extract the images to the local /content/data directory.
Step B: Preprocessing & Augmentation: Run the ImageDataGenerator section. This will resize your images to $224\times224$ and apply transformations like rotation and flipping to improve model generalization.
Step C: Build & Train: This section initializes the VGG16 base model with ImageNet weights, adds custom layers, and begins training for 15 epochs.
Step D: Evaluation: Run the confusion matrix and classification report blocks to see the precision, recall, and overall accuracy (targeted at 94-95%).
Step E: Visualizations: Run the Grad-CAM and plot blocks to visualize the heatmaps (which highlight where the model is "looking" on the MRI) and accuracy graphs.

4. Launch the Gradio Interface
The final block launches a web-based UI.Run the Gradio cell.
Wait for the Running on public URL: link to appear.
Click the link or use the interface embedded in the cell to upload an MRI image and see real-time predictions.

Required LibrariesThe code uses several key libraries that are pre-installed in Colab, but ensure your environment has them:
tensorflow & keras (Deep Learning) 
cv2 (OpenCV for image processing) 
gradio (User interface) 
matplotlib & numpy (Data handling and visualization)
Note: If you encounter an error saying gradio is not found, add a cell at the very top with !pip install gradio and run it first.
